        [
          "Staff Generated History"
        ],
        [
          "Your dad was a highly ranked military officer, just like your uncle, just like your grandfather, just like your great-grandfather.  So you went to military school, because that was what was expected.  And even though you hated it, you got through it because that was what was expected.   And then you joined the military, because that was what was expected. And even though you were neither physically nor temperamentally suited for it, you did the work because that was what was expected.  Family connections sure helped, and so did being glib and articulate.  Eventually you rose in rank and took on more and more administrative responsibility.  You learned how to game the system and work it to your advantage.  That made it bearable, and let you give your famnily what was expected.     Your skill gaming the system got you noticed.  And then there were a whole new range of expectations from your sire.  Who made your boot camp drill instructor, the martinet of a base commander at your first post, and your own awful father look like the three little pigs.   You had resigned yourself to an eternity of managing your sire's wide-ranging connections and influences, leveraging your own people skills for his monstrous ends.  Then Valentin and the rest of the pack turned up after you'd moved with your sire to Worcester.   They saved you, and you're really grateful.   But even though you hated him, your sire's screams still haunt you.  And worse, your sire's many influential friends still haunt you.   They're not hunting you, exactly, but you need to keep your head down because your sire was part of a very powerful lineage, and your pack deprived some very powerful Elders of a very useful tool.   And now they're upset wtih you in particular.   Your packmates tell you that you've all struck a blow for freedom.  But you're not sure the price was worth it.   That said you're new to the Sabbat and still finding your way.   You still cling to your humanity, but also know you need some other way to manage your unlife.   Look how clinging to humanity worked out for your sire.  You tell yourself you'll never end up as bad as him, but really?  Who knows?"
        ],
